<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06103115 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06103115 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  PROFESSIONAL; HOCKEY; CLUB; SF-BAY-AREA; COACH; APPOINTMENT; PROFILE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The Sharks named George Kingston, coach of Norway's national team and a formerNHL assistant, as the team's first coach today.;    Kingston, 51, spent thelast two years as Norway's coach and as sports director of the Norwegian IceHockey Federation. A native of Biggar, Saskatchewan, he has spent most of hiscareer coaching in Canada, including 19 years as head coach at the Universityof Calgary, where his team won five conference titles. While there, he workedas a part-time assistant with the Calgary Flames of the National Hockey Leaguefrom 1980 to 1982.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  SHARKS NAME VETERAN KINGSTON AS COACH  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     His other NHL experience came as an assistant coach with the MinnesotaNorth Stars in 1988-89, when Sharks General Manager Jack Ferreira was theMinnesota general manager.;    &quot;George's involvement on all levels of hockeymakes him the perfect coach for an expansion franchise like ours,&quot; saidFerreira, who also serves as the Sharks' executive vice president. &quot;He knowshow to teach and develop players on every caliber and has proven to be verypatient and thorough.&quot;;    Kingston said today he &quot;enjoyed coaching universityhockey, but was also interested in making the international game and the NHLthe next levels to test. The time I spent in Norway was a good opportunity toimprove the efficiency of my coaching.;    &quot;I'm becoming an NHL head coachgoing in with the right people in scouting, management and ownership, so I'mvery comfortable with this step in my career.&quot;;    Kingston also has workedwith the Canadian national team, working as an assistant coach for Canada'sOlympic team in 1984, and was the chairman of the 1988 Olympic tournament inCalgary, Alberta.;    While in Norway, Kingston has been working as a Europeanscout for the Sharks. And his knowledge of European players will be usefulduring the NHL entry draft, which takes place June 22 in Buffalo, N.Y. NorthAmerican amateurs and all European players are eligible for the entry draft.;   Kingston also has said he believes it would take from five to seven years tobuild an expansion team such as the Sharks into a Stanley Cup contender. Andhe has said a long-term commitment from the team would be important to him.;   Kingston's relationship with Ferreira dates to the early 1980s, when Ferreirawas a scout for the Calgary Flames. And Kingston has praised the track recordof Ferreira, who was successful with the Flames and New York Rangers beforejoining the North Stars in 1988.;    &quot;Jack knows what it takes to besuccessful,&quot; Kingston has said. &quot;Before I would take any new job, I would wantto make sure I was getting involved with the right people. That's onecondition that I'm sure would be met in San Jose.&quot;; Kingston, who is marriedwith two adult children, is an avid runner, competing in ultra-marathons,50-100 mile races run over rugged terrain. He also has background as aneducator, including 21 years as a professor at the University of Calgary,where he was associate academic dean from 1975 to 1988. He has a doctorate inphilosophy from the University of Alberta at Edmonton.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  MIKE WEAVER, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910412  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  April  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1D  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  520  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Friday April 12, 199100103115,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>